t, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Winchett Hall, Goudhurst, Kent, England":"Goudhurst, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Roberts","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the personal name   Robert  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is also occasionally borne by Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Robert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Marcel, Gilles, Normand, Armand, Lucien, Pierre, Emile, Michel, Edouard, Gaston, Yves.","French, Walloon, English, German, Dutch, Flemish, and Breton (of French origin); Hungarian (<b>Róbert</b>): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Ro(d)bert</i> (Middle English <i>Robert</i>, Old French <i>Ro(d)bert</i>), composed of the elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This is found occasionally in Anglo-Saxon England before the Conquest, but in the main it was introduced into England by the Normans and quickly became popular among all classes of society. Pet forms and diminutives are found from an early date,   Robin   being particularly common. Compare   Robair  ,   Robar  ,   Robare  , and   Rober  .","In some cases also an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]},{"name":"Robers","meanings":["English: variant of   Roberts  ."]},{"name":"Roberds","meanings":["English: variant of   Roberts  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Robards","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Roberts  ."]},{"name":"Robarts","meanings":["English (Bedfordshire and Hertfortshire): variant of   Roberts  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Roberts de Rookehurste was born in 1330, in Goudhurst, Kent, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Robertes of Rookehurste, was 30 and his mother, Lady Unknown, was 29. He married Isabel Culpeper in 1350, in Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1380, in his hometown, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1330–1380":"1330–1380","1334–Female":"1334–Surnud","1350–1441":"1350–1441","1300–1360":"1300–1360","1301–1360":"1301–1360","1301":"1301","1334":"1334","1300":"1300","1441":"1441","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","Glassenbury Manor, Cranbrook, Kent, England":"Cranbrook, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Goudhurst, Kent, England":"Goudhurst, Kent, 